<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-587-597  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 587 597.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 5 1990 v24 n44 p103(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Between now and ideal. (future trends in imaging systemdevelopment) (Image Processing Systems Special Report)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Booker, Ellis; Ryan, Alan J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The future development of electronic document imaging systems isbound to include increased price/performance ratios for componentequipment, as well as improved software, expanded system range,and more advanced imaging tools.andP;  Companies that currently useimage processing for specific applications will want to extend itsutility over the enterprise.andP;  Issues of compatibility will becrucial since the technology still lacks standards.andP;  Optical diskstorage should boast increased capacity due to improved lasers,and the median access time for disks is expected to drop.andP;  Opticalcharacter recognition components will also improve, gaining theability to read more printed fonts and even handwriting.andP;  Thesoftware tools used to develop imaging applications are expectedto be critical to the overall success of imaging systems, makingit quicker and easier to use image processing equipment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Storage and RetrievalImage processingTrendsFuture of ComputingDocument ProcessingEquipment AcquisitionComputer industryProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablecartoon.andO;Caption:   Investment by industry: 1993. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>